{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17584725","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17584725"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T07:55:08+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T07:55:08+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14790"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14790","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14790"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.13,0.67,0.1,0.08,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7481"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"58632"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7481","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7481"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14790"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"44034"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4927"},{"type":"tags","id":"4940"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"5071"},{"type":"tags","id":"7603"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"18303"},{"type":"contributions","id":"18305"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"58632","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/58632"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA medical student is studying the mechanism of action of salbutamol, a short-acting beta-2 agonist.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the cellular mechanism of action of salbutamol?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Blocks calcium channels to prevent muscle contraction","Activates G-protein coupled receptor to increase cyclic adenosine monophosphate","Inhibits phosphodiesterase to prevent cyclic adenosine monophosphate breakdown","Stimulates muscarinic receptors to increase acetylcholine release","Opens potassium channels directly to cause hyperpolarisation"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EShort-acting beta-2 agonists (SABAs) like salbutamol work by binding to beta-2 adrenergic receptors on smooth muscle cells. These receptors are \u003Cstrong\u003EG-protein coupled receptors\u003C/strong\u003E that, when activated, \u003Cstrong\u003Estimulate adenylyl cyclase to produce cyclic adenosine monophosphate (cAMP)\u003C/strong\u003E. This leads to smooth muscle relaxation. Side effects of SABAs include tremor, tachycardia, and hypokalaemia due to beta-2 receptor activation in other tissues.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESABAs do not primarily work by \u003Cstrong\u003Eblocking calcium channels\u003C/strong\u003E, though increased cAMP does reduce intracellular calcium. They are distinct from drugs that \u003Cstrong\u003Einhibit phosphodiesterase\u003C/strong\u003E like theophylline, and also do not \u003Cstrong\u003Estimulate muscarinic receptors\u003C/strong\u003E (this would cause smooth muscle contraction). Short-acting beta-2 agonists do not directly \u003Cstrong\u003Eopen potassium channels\u003C/strong\u003E, though this may occur downstream of cAMP activation. \u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Short-acting beta-2 agonists cause smooth muscle relaxation in bronchi and uterus through activation of beta-2 adrenergic receptors.","Beta-2 agonists increase intracellular cyclic adenosine monophosphate (cAMP) through G-protein coupled receptor signaling.","Common side effects of beta-2 agonists include tremor, tachycardia, and hypokalaemia."],"references":["Therapeutic Guidelines. Melbourne: Therapeutic Guidelines Limited. Available from: https://www.tg.org.au","Australian Medicines Handbook\u00a0(online). Adelaide: Australian Medicines Handbook Pty Ltd. Available from:\u00a0https://amhonline.amh.net.au/","Ritter J, Flower RJ (Rod J), Henderson G (Graeme), et al.\u00a0Rang and Dale\u2019s Pharmacology. Tenth edition. Elsevier; 2024."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"44034"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14790"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"44034","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/44034"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-02T08:50:19+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-02T08:50:51+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7481"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"58632"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4927","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4927"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec1","name":"Respiratory","synonyms":[],"description":nu